Post
thoughts:
This is the first album of the three that we’ve gone through so far that I’d probably come back to. I’d never listened to Björk before and this record made me think of two things: Fiona Apple and The Matrix soundtrack. Björk doesn’t sound like Fiona Apple, but their music feels dynamic in a similar way, and they both throw tons of ideas into their songs. There are big band horns and congas and crazy techno stuff, and I really loved the range of sounds and styles on each of the tracks. There's also something very physical about both of their voices.

I was trying to figure out why I thought of the The Matrix soundtrack and I realized that both albums have elements of Trip hop (I was probably thinking of Clubbed to Death). It’s a style that I associate with the 90s and makes what otherwise feels to me like a very progressive and experimental album, even in 2021, seem a little dated.

Favorite songs: Possibly Maybe, It’s Oh so Quiet, Hyperballad, I Miss You

Mix of very positive feelings about some songs (esp Hyperballad) and strong negative feelings about other songs (can't remember which though). Appropriate amount of angst for long walks in COVID winter, would listen again.

title: Sweetheart of the Rodeo
thoughts:
long-haired hippies, a bit repetitive, nice instrumental sections

Yeah, great backing musicians (shoutout to John Hartford!). This album also has some songs in it that really hit my personal sweet spot of upbeat melodies with depressing lyrics.

So I'd do life in prison for the wrongs I've done
And I pray every night for death to come
My life will be a burden every day
If I could die, my pain might go away

That's some great stuff right there. I dislike the lead singer's voice very much. I don't think the Byrds actually wrote any of the songs on this album? Seems like mostly traditional and country tunes written by other people.
